{"title_page": "Tornado outbreak of October 20\u201322, 2019", "text_new": "{{Infobox storm\n| name = Tornado outbreak of October 20\u201322, 2019\n| highest winds = Tornadic: {{convert|140|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} <small>(Dallas, TX EF3 tornado)</small><br>Non-tornadic: {{convert|82|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} <small>(SSW of [[Hoffman, Oklahoma]])</small>\n| enhanced = yes\n| current advisories = \n| affected = [[South Central United States]], [[Southeastern United States]]\n| total fatalities =\n| power outages =\n| maximum snow =\n| gusts =\n| hail = {{convert|2.75|in|mm|abbr=on}} <small>([[Milburn, Oklahoma|Milburn]] and [[Prague, Oklahoma]])</small>\n| tornado duration = 24 hours\n| image = October 20\u201323, 2019 tornado outbreak warnings and reports.png\n| fujitascale = EF3\n| tornadoes = 36\n| lowest temperature =\n| lowest pressure = \n| active = October 20, 2019 - October 22, 2019\n| type = [[Tornado outbreak]]\n| caption = Map of tornado warnings and confirmed tornadoes from the outbreak\n| alt = \n| partof = the '''[[Tornadoes of 2019|tornado outbreaks of 2019]]'''\n}}\nThe '''tornado outbreak of October 20\u201322, 2019''' was a significant severe weather event across the [[South Central United States]]. Forecasters first identified the threat on October&nbsp;16 as a large upper-level [[Trough (meteorology)|trough]] was expected to combine with an unstable atmosphere across Texas, Oklahoma, and Arkansas particularly. On the evening of October&nbsp;20, discrete [[supercell]] thunderstorms developed across the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]], contributing to several tornadoes. One of those tornadoes caused EF3 damage in the Dallas suburbs, becoming the costliest tornado event in Texas history, at $1.55&nbsp;billion. A later [[squall line]] contributed to additional tornadoes and a widespread swath of damaging winds as the system tracked eastward.\n\n==Meteorological synopsis==\nThe first signs of organized severe weather across the [[South Central United States]] came on October&nbsp;16, when the [[Storm Prediction Center]] (SPC) first delineated a risk area across portions of northern Texas, eastern Oklahoma, and adjacent portions of Kansas, Missouri, and Arkansas.<ref>{{cite web|author=Elizabeth Leitman|title=Day 4-8 Severe Weather Outlook Issued on Oct 16, 2019|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/exper/day4-8/archive/2019/day4-8_20191016.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=October 16, 2019|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> In their day&nbsp;3 outlook on October&nbsp;18, the organization introduced a broad Marginal risk for much of the same areas.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brynn Kerr|title=Oct 18, 2019 0730 UTC Day 3 Severe Thunderstorm Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day3otlk_20191018_0730.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=October 18, 2019|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> A small Slight risk was added across northeastern Texas, southeastern Oklahoma, and western Arkansas on October&nbsp;19,<ref>{{cite web|author=Brynn Kerr|title=Oct 19, 2019 0600 UTC Day 2 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day2otlk_20191019_0600.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=October 19, 2019|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> but as confidence in a higher-end event increased, these same areas were raised to an Enhanced risk.<ref name=\"d1\">{{cite web|author=Roger Edwards|author2=Andy Dean|title=Oct 20, 2019 1300 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2019/day1otlk_20191020_1300.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=October 20, 2019|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> In advance of the outbreak, the SPC monitored several weather features of interest. In the upper levels of the atmosphere, an upper-level [[Trough (meteorology)|trough]] was expected to amplify as it progressed eastward into the U.S. Plains, providing increasing wind shear throughout the region. Simultaneously, a [[low-pressure area]] and associated [[cold front]] were anticipated to shift eastward across an unstable environment, leading to the formation of severe thunderstorms. Forecasters noted that while the overall environment supported the potential for significant ([[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF2+]]) tornadoes, questions about whether storms would be supercellular or instead evolve into a [[quasi-linear convective system]] prevented the addition a significant risk area.<ref name=\"d1\" /> By the late afternoon hours of October&nbsp;20, thunderstorms began to develop across eastern Oklahoma within a rapidly-moistening environment.<ref>{{cite web|author=Matt Mosier|author2=Jeremy Grams|title=Mesoscale Discussion 2089|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/2019/md2089.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=October 20, 2019|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> At 7:58&nbsp;p.m. CDT, the first [[tornado watch]] was issued across the [[Ark-La-Tex]] region;<ref>{{cite web|title=Tornado Watch 676|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/2019/ww0676.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=October 20, 2019|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> several more watches were introduced over subsequent hours.<ref>{{cite web|title=SPC Severe Weather Event Review for Sunday October 20 2019|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/exper/archive/event.php?date=20191020|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=October 20, 2019|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> A pair of long-tracked supercells developed across [[Tarrant County, Texas|Tarrant]] and [[Johnson County, Texas|Johnson]] counties, intersecting a very unstable regime and producing significant tornadoes as a result.<ref>{{cite web|author=Matt Mosier|title=Mesoscale Discussion 2090|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/md/2019/md2090.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=October 20, 2019|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> A squall line formed along the cold front farther west, producing a wide swath of damaging winds and additional tornadoes as it tracked across the South-Central United States.<ref name=\"dallas\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=Texas Event Report: EF3 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=856409|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=SPC Storm Reports for 10/20/19|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/191020_rpts.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=October 20, 2019|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Confirmed tornadoes==\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 36\n|FU = 0\n|F0 = 13\n|F1 = 20\n|F2 = 2\n|F3 = 1\n|F4 = 0\n|F5 = 0\n|Enhanced=yes\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|+ Confirmed tornadoes during the tornado outbreak of October 20\u201322, 2019{{efn|All dates are based on the local [[time zone]] where the tornado touched down; however, all times are in [[Coordinated Universal Time]] for consistency.|group=note|name=Date/Time}}\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|[[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF#]]\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:7%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|Location\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|County / Parish\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:5%; text-align:center;\"|State\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Start Coord.\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"7%\" align=\"center\"|Date\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Time ([[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]])\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Path length\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Max width\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:48%; text-align:center;\"|Summary\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|Refs\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|SW of [[Beckville, Texas|Beckville]]\n|[[Panola County, Texas|Panola]]\n|[[Texas|TX]]\n|{{Coord|32.1470|-94.5443|name=Beckville (Oct. 20, EF0)}}\n|{{Sort|001|October&nbsp;20}}\n|00:36\u201300:38\n|{{convert|0.8|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|150|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Several trees were snapped or uprooted. A home's roof was damaged.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana|title=Texas Event Report: EF0 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=854764|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|SSE of [[Greenwood, Louisiana|Greenwood]]\n|[[Caddo Parish, Louisiana|Caddo]]\n|[[Louisiana|LA]]\n|{{Coord|32.3738|-93.976|name=Greenwood (Oct. 20, EF1)}}\n|{{Sort|002|October&nbsp;20}}\n|01:42\u201301:49\n|{{convert|3.59|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|350|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|A greenhouse was destroyed, shingled were ripped off the roofs of two homes, and an RV trailer was rolled onto its side. Numerous trees were snapped or uprooted.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana|title=Louisiana Event Report: EF1 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=855002|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat3}} | EF3\n|[[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] to [[Richardson, Texas|Richardson]]\n|[[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas]]\n|[[Texas|TX]]\n|{{Coord|32.8685|-96.9149|name=Dallas (Oct. 20, EF3)}}\n|{{Sort|003|October&nbsp;20}}\n|01:58\u201302:30\n|{{convert|15.76|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|1300|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|[[Tornado outbreak of October 20\u201322, 2019#Dallas-Richardson, Texas|See section on this tornado]]\n|<ref name=\"dallas\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|N of [[Midlothian, Texas|Midlothian]]\n|[[Ellis County, Texas|Ellis]]\n|[[Texas|TX]]\n|{{Coord|32.4981|-96.9935|name=Midlothian (Oct. 20, EF1)}}\n|{{Sort|004|October&nbsp;20}}\n|02:10\u201302:15\n|{{convert|2.83|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|350|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Several church and retail buildings had their roofs damaged and windows blown out. One structure attached to the church was severely damaged as most of its roof was ripped off, and its south-facing wall was collapsed. Two buildings had sheet metal peeled away, while one of the structures had its metal roof purlins bent. Several homes suffered significant roof damage and had windows blown out, one  of which had its garage door collapsed. Trees were snapped or uprooted as well.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=Texas Event Report: EF1 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=856475|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat2}} | EF2\n|[[Garland, Texas|Garland]]\n|[[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas]]\n|[[Texas|TX]]\n|{{Coord|32.8974|-96.6753|name=Garland (Oct. 20, EF2)}}\n|{{Sort|005|October&nbsp;20}}\n|02:24\u201302:30\n|{{convert|2.48|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|265|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|This high-end tornado caused significant damage in Garland. A wide section of the roof to a Sear's Facility warehouse was peeled off, tearing away the adjacent metal walls and causing some of the interior support columns and beams to bend. An empty 18-wheeler and a van were tipped onto their sides. Nearby, a newly-built warehouse collapsed as its support columns were bent to the ground. debris from this structure caused additional damage to nearby homes. Along the remainder of the tornado path, numerous homes were heavily damaged, some of which had their roofs torn off. Many trees were snapped or uprooted as well.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=Texas Event Report: EF2 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=856477|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|[[Rowlett, Texas|Rowlett]] to [[Wylie, Texas|Wylie]]\n|[[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas]]\n|[[Texas|TX]]\n|{{Coord|32.9237|-96.5697|name=Rowlett (Oct. 20, EF1)}}\n|{{Sort|006|October&nbsp;20}}\n|02:36\u201302:45\n|{{convert|6.02|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|500|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|This high-end EF1 tornado moved through residential areas, damaging numerous homes. Some homes had large portions of their roofs torn off. Several outbuildings were also damaged or destroyed, and trees were downed.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=Texas Event Report: EF1 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=856502|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|W of [[Ferris, Texas|Ferris]]\n|[[Ellis County, Texas|Ellis]]\n|[[Texas|TX]]\n|{{Coord|32.5332|-96.6664|name=Ferris (Oct. 20, EF0)}}\n|{{Sort|007|October&nbsp;20}}\n|02:42\u201302:44\n|{{convert|0.18|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|170|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|A silo was damaged and partially collapsed, multiple businesses sustained roof damage, a power pole was downed, and trees were snapped or uprooted.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=Texas Event Report: EF0 Tornado|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=856503|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2019|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|[[Rockwall, Texas|Rockwall]]\n|[[Rockwall County, Texas|Ro